Now our philosophy here was the farmers would do it all and nobody was going to put any money on them.
They went over here in this one in Houston County
which was a beautiful community setup, and gave them, I think, $10,000.
And the next thing I knew, they were having a squabble on how they were going to spend that $10,000, and the thing blew up.
But at any rate, Bill didn't have any use for them.
And I had to have a job.
And I did a little farming back some 15 and a half years ago.
And I started digging into soils, soil improvement and fertilizers.
And when I quit in 57, I was the recognized authority in agriculture on the three.

demonstrations according to the plans that I drew up.
And when I say I drew up, I'm the finest corn grower in Nacogdoches County.
I said, well, that's fine.
I'm glad to meet you.

four times with it.

I saw this old duck
unloading some fertilizer that I had authorized to be shipped in.

I said, have you ever used fertilizer?
Yes, sir.
How much do you use?
400 pounds to the acres, the finest fertilizer in the world.
I said, don't it burn the stuff up?

So, as I said, back in 1935 or 1936, I got us a portable soil testing kit.
didn't take me long to see that these kits that were built up in the northern states just weren't worth a nickel in Texas.
We had different conditions, so I took off and built my own.
And the result of my work and
the work being done under Fudge in the state chemist's lab.

Asbury?

No, let's let that ride.

Oh, I built this kit, and I would go out to this farm and take soil samples and test them.
And he wouldn't believe them.
Certainly not.
That's brand new stuff.
He didn't do that.
So I'd go and take this growing cotton.
I'd go get a half a dozen leaves.
off of this cotton that's just going to make about one bale and ten acres.

Now, I kept that up.
There are a lot of interesting stories there that come up with
as you go along through that.
And in 1950, I guess it was, they talked the state chemist into running the analyses with the understanding that I wrote the recommendations.
Now, in order to get the state chemist to do that, it took lots of doing.
Because Fraps insisted there was no way in the world you could run a soil test and predict what happened.
And he fought soil testing with everything that he had.
Well, his successor Fudge was a little more liberal.
And when I yanked him out of his marble chair and took him out in the country with me, I let him see what was going on.
He then decided that he would go into it, and they went into it with the understanding that every soil sample was a dollar, which was all right.
But that still wasn't satisfactory, so I, with another fellow, as I said, I can't think of his name, took a trip around the states that were using soil testing to get their ideas.
among which was Oklahoma, Arkansas, Mississippi, Kentucky, Illinois, Iowa, and Missouri.
We came back here and set up the laboratory we have here.
I go to the laboratory here now and see what they're doing.
It's amazing.
Back in those days, we did everything by
strong methods and awkwardness.
Nowadays, you've got these electronic machines.
They'll run the soil out now and give you analyses on that thing there that I never dreamed of.
As I said, that's part of this thing that I mentioned way back here.
The chemistry is just boiling.
And what you're up to data in today, you're out of data on tomorrow.
And that's the way it ought to be.
That's fine.

The radio tower on top of Milne Hall was put in, I would say, about 19, the summer of 1913 or maybe 14.
And one morning we woke up.
And a young fellow, his name was Cohen, rode a bicycle to and from work.
And that darn bicycle was tied to the top of that radio tower.
How in the name of common sense that bunch got that bicycle up there, I'll never know.
They finally got it down, and I guess the fellow put it up there is the one who brought it down.
But now there is something.
That is just one thing.
Well, there's another one.
If you'll notice on Milner Hall, there's little alcoves up there.
Came along one morning going to work, and there was a shut-lit pony in that alcove on the third floor.
You couldn't have walked him up there.
How in the world they got him up there, I'll never know.
I had to...
Just sitting here, as I said, thinking there'll be some others just as wild.
You can cut it off now.
When I first came here in the spring months, the band would meet every Sunday afternoon in the bandstand that was out on the edge of the drill field.
And people from Brown would drive out in their horses and buggies.
And Goodman Hall was over there as a dormitory.
And boys would be sticking out, looking at that, and just as sure as they had one of those, one of those boys would presumably fall out a window.
They'd take their dummy and dress him up, and when they got down to the right point, they'd push him out.
And finally, I break up that damn chance.
As I said, back then, we organized a basketball team.
But the first thing we did in fall of 1912, I guess it was, we organized a football team.
On that football team, we had an All-American from Cornell.
all Missouri Valley, Iowa, all southern, center, and South Carolina.
In other words, it was made up of a bunch of fellows that taught here that had played football and knew the way around.
But, you know, we couldn't get with 11 men.
So, well, no, we couldn't get 11.
We had two that we organized as standing guards.
With this bird, you know, at Thermopylae, you stand up there and need not let him pass.
And their jobs were not to let anybody through.
They did nothing about football, but they're both powerful men.
And just don't let that other fellow through.
You just take care of him.
And be sure you get the man that's got the football.
The others,
played and the rest of us ran the team.
Tommy Ogier was quarterback.
Who was that?
Tommy Ogier.
You never heard of him?
No, I haven't.
He died here about three or four years ago.
Well, we went out there and played the C Company and they thought a good chance to get even with the professors.

The half of us didn't realize they were working fellows that had cut their teeth in big-time football, and for a little amateur company team to haul off and rough them up a little bit was just asking for trouble.
So the morning after they played the C Company, there were about 15 in the hospital.
And the next time we played was the band.
And the same thing happened.
I know most of the band was in the hospital.
And we weren't hurt.
We were just taking the thing in the stride.
Then Charlie Moran decided that I didn't, he says, I don't have a game for Saturday.
How about you fellas playing Thursday or Friday?
Playing the reserves, not the first team.
Now a lot of boys think it's the first team.
It wasn't the first team.
Doggone it that morning before we were going to play, our center, Missouri Valley, had to have an appendix out.
And they had a fellow they could put out on end that had a little sense about football but not a whole lot.
So they elected me to take that center place.
And I can assure you the fellow that was playing on the other side was using something beside his body.
I think he had a club in his hand where it could be over.
But man, oh man, the reserves beat us five to nothing just because that doggone replacement of mine let the halfback on the reserve team get outside him.
And they finally brought him down
on about the five yard line, and they did put the cross, they earned it, but we couldn't score.
Next morning, President Miller issued one of the many foolish edicts that comes out of the president's office.
He said, in the future, no member of the teaching staff will participate in any
hazardous or dangerous games.
That is the most foolish thing that ever happened.
If you'd have handed a football at any of them, they'd have turned the ball like that.
They wouldn't have even touched it.
Man, how wicked we took.
Five to nothing.
It wasn't a bad game.
But that was the cleanest game we played.
The games against the company teams.
The boys didn't use their head.
But against the reserves, it was a clean game.
But they were hitting and they were hitting hard.
